andie, Frankrijk","Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 0987–1058":"about 0987–1058","0980–1027":"0980–1027","1000–1062":"1000–1062","1005–1086":"1005–1086","0987–1058":"0987–1058","1005":"1005","1027":"1027","1058":"1058","about 0987":"about 0987","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","Abt 1005":"about 1005","Abt 1027":"about 1027","1086":"1086","1062":"1062","0987":"0987","about 1000":"about 1000","Préaux, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Préaux, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harcourt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the places in Eure and Calvados named Harcourt, from Old French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) with an obscure first element. This surname is very rare in France.","English: habitational name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Villes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: patronymic from   Nill   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Nill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Ulrich.","North German: from a personal name, a shortened form of   Cornelius  .","South German: nickname for a big, crude or unmannered person, related to Middle High German <i>nol</i> ‘rounded elevation’."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Albreda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Elfreda  , but now probably taken as a feminine equivalent of   Alfred ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Albreda Harcourt de Villes de Beaumont was born about 0987, in Préaux, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France. She had at least 2 sons with Eudes de Rye. She died in 1058, in Normandy, France, at the age of 72."},"et":{"about 0987–1058":"umbes 0987–1058","0980–1027":"0980–1027","1000–1062":"1000–1062","1005–1086":"1005–1086","0987–1058":"0987–1058","1005":"1005","1027":"1027","1058":"1058","about 0987":"umbes 0987","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","Abt 1005":"umbes 1005","Abt 1027":"umbes 1027","1086":"1086","1062":"1062","0987":"0987","about 1000":"umbes 1000","Préaux, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Préaux, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 0987–1058":"noin 0987–1058","0980–1027":"0980–1027","1000–1062":"1000–1062","1005–1086":"1005–1086","0987–1058":"0987–1058","100